We have $f =_a\mu_L g$ and $g =_a\mu_L h$, so we need to prove $f =_a\mu_L h$.

Let's expand the definition of $f =_a\mu_L h$.

This means $\mu_L(\{x \in \mathbb{R} \mid f(x) \neq h(x)\}) = 0$.

We know:
1. $\mu_L(\{x \mid f(x) \neq g(x)\}) = 0$ from $f =_a\mu_L g$.
2. $\mu_L(\{x \mid g(x) \neq h(x)\}) = 0$ from $g =_a\mu_L h$.

Let's consider the set $\{x \mid f(x) \neq h(x)\}$.

If $f(x) \neq h(x)$, then $f(x) \neq g(x)$ or $g(x) \neq h(x)$.

Therefore, $\{x \mid f(x) \neq h(x)\} \subseteq \{x \mid f(x) \neq g(x)\} \cup \{x \mid g(x) \neq h(x)\}$.

So $\mu_L(\{x \mid f(x) \neq h(x)\}) \leq \mu_L(\{x \mid f(x) \neq g(x)\} \cup \{x \mid g(x) \neq h(x)\})$.

Using the subadditivity of the Lebesgue measure:
